    "text": "The WorldLines paper describes memory-to-plan translation as a component designed to reconstruct a coherent world model when state overwrites occur due to partial observability.",
    "topic": "Role of memory-to-plan translation in WorldLines"
  },
  {
    "text": "The paper does not argue that memory-to-plan translation is required for agents that do not maintain a persistent world model or that operate with full observability.",
    "topic": "Limitation of the claim"
  },
  {
    "text": "In WorldLines, memory-to-plan translation is presented as part of a specific architecture to mitigate the effects of partial observability and memory overwriting, not as a universal principle for all embodied agents.",
    "topic": "Scope of the technique"
  },
  {
    "text": "The phrase 'memory-to-plan translation' is used in the context of converting episodic memory into actionable plans after detecting inconsistencies between observed and predicted world states.",
    "topic": "Definition in context"
  }
]
